fields.about_section_content:
At Deigratia Montessori School, we believe in nurturing the whole child through the proven Montessori method. Our approach focuses on:

  • Child-centered learning environment
  • Mixed-age classrooms that foster peer learning
  • Hands-on learning materials
  • Respect for the child's natural development
  • Experienced and certified Montessori educators

fields.title: School Exhibition 2025 - Showcase of Excellence
fields.content:
We are excited to announce our annual School Exhibition taking place next month! This is a wonderful opportunity for our students to showcase their learning journey and achievements throughout the academic year.

Event Highlights:

  • Student project displays from all grade levels
  • Science experiments and demonstrations
  • Art and creative works exhibition
  • Technology and robotics showcase
  • Cultural performances

Parents, families, and community members are cordially invited to attend this celebration of learning and achievement.

fields.title: Science Day Celebration - Exploring the Wonders of Science
fields.content:
Join us for an exciting Science Day celebration where our young scientists will demonstrate their understanding of scientific concepts through hands-on experiments and presentations.

Activities Include:

  • Interactive science experiments
  • Student-led demonstrations
  • Science fair projects
  • Guest scientist presentations
  • Fun science games and activities

This event promotes scientific thinking and curiosity among our students while making learning fun and engaging.

fields.title: New STEM Laboratory Now Open
fields.content:
We are thrilled to announce the opening of our new state-of-the-art STEM laboratory! This modern facility will enhance our students' learning experience in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics.

Laboratory Features:

  • Advanced robotics equipment
  • Computer programming stations
  • 3D printing capabilities
  • Interactive science equipment
  • Collaborative learning spaces

This investment in our infrastructure demonstrates our commitment to providing world-class education for our students.

fields.title: Output Devices
fields.description: Output devices are tools that allow a computer to display, print, or send information to users. They help us see, hear, or feel the results of what we do on a computer. This lesson will explain what output devices are, how they work, and why they are important in ICT.
fields.content:
Introduction to Output Devices

An output device is a hardware tool that a computer uses to send information back to us. It helps us understand the results of our actions on a computer. Without output devices, we wouldn't be able to see images, read text, hear sounds, or print documents.

Types of Output Devices

Here are some important output devices:

  1. Monitor (Screen) – Shows pictures, videos, and text.

  2. Speakers – Play sounds, music, or voices from the computer.

  3. Printer – Prints words or pictures onto paper.

  4. Projector – Displays images on a larger screen or wall.

  5. Headphones – Let us hear sounds privately.

  6. Braille Display – Helps visually impaired people read by using raised dots.

Why Output Devices Matter

Output devices help us:

  • See documents and pictures on a screen.

  • Hear sounds or music through speakers.

  • Print important papers using a printer.

  • Share presentations using a projector.

How Output Devices Work

  1. We give a command using input devices (like a keyboard or mouse).

  2. The computer processes the command.

  3. The computer sends the result through output devices.

Example:

  • If you type a message (input), it appears on the screen (output).

  • If you play music (input), you hear the sound through speakers (output).

  • If you draw a picture (input), you can print it using a printer (output).

Activity: Find the Output Devices!

identify output devices around You at school or home.

Fun Fact

Did you know? The first computers didn’t have screens! People had to read punched cards or listen to sounds to understand what the computer was doing. Today, we use colorful monitors, speakers, and even smart glasses as output devices!

fields.title: Introduction to ICT
fields.description: dgms
fields.content:
What is ICT?

ICT stands for Information and Communication Technology. It is all about using computers and other electronic devices to share and find information. It makes our lives easier by helping us talk to people, learn new things, and solve problems.

 

What is Input?

In ICT, input means giving instructions or information to a computer or device. We use special tools to do this—called input devices.

Examples of Input Devices:

  1. Keyboard: For typing letters, numbers, and symbols.

  2. Mouse: For pointing, clicking, and selecting things on the screen.

  3. Touchscreen: For tapping or drawing on the screen (like on a tablet or phone).

  4. Microphone: For recording your voice or sounds.

  5. Camera: For taking pictures or making videos.

  6. Scanner: For copying papers or pictures into the computer.

 

Why is Input Important?

Input helps the computer understand what we want to do. Without input, the computer wouldn't know:

  • What to type in a message.

  • Which picture to show.

  • What sounds to record.

 

How Input Works

  1. We give information using input devices.

  2. The computer receives the information.

  3. It uses the information to do what we ask it to—like showing a photo or writing a story.

 

Activity: Let's Spot Input Devices!

Ask your students to look around the classroom or at home and find objects that can be used as input devices (like keyboards, mice, or microphones). You can make it fun by turning it into a game or a competition!

 

Extra Fun Fact

Did you know? Long ago, computers were so big that they took up entire rooms—and people gave them input by punching holes in paper cards. Now we just use small devices like keyboards and touchscreens!

fields.title: New In the IT
fields.content:
Components of the System Unit and the Keyboard

1. The System Unit

The system unit is the main part of a desktop computer. It is a box-like case that contains the core components responsible for processing data. It is sometimes referred to as the CPU case or computer chassis.

Key Components Inside the System Unit:

  • Central Processing Unit (CPU): Known as the "brain" of the computer, the CPU performs all the calculations and processing tasks.

  • Motherboard: This is the main circuit board that connects all the internal components such as the CPU, memory, and storage devices.

  • Random Access Memory (RAM): RAM is the computer’s short-term memory. It stores data temporarily while tasks are being performed.

  • Storage Devices (Hard Drive or SSD): These are used to store data permanently. SSDs are faster than traditional hard drives.

  • Power Supply Unit (PSU): This component converts electrical power from the outlet into usable power for the computer’s internal parts.

  • Cooling Fans/Heat Sink: These help keep the computer cool and prevent overheating of components like the CPU.

2. The Keyboard

The keyboard is one of the primary input devices used to enter data into a computer. It consists of keys for letters, numbers, symbols, and special functions.

Types of Keys on the Keyboard:

  • Alphabet Keys (A-Z): Used to type letters and words.

  • Number Keys (0-9): For entering numerical data.

  • Function Keys (F1 to F12): Perform special tasks depending on the software in use.

  • Special Keys:

    • Enter: Moves the cursor to a new line or executes commands.

    • Backspace: Deletes the character to the left of the cursor.

    • Delete: Removes the character to the right of the cursor.

    • Shift: Used to type uppercase letters or access the top symbol on a key.

    • Ctrl, Alt, Esc: Used in combination with other keys to perform specific commands.

  • Arrow Keys: Move the cursor in different directions.

  • Caps Lock: When activated, types all letters in uppercase.

Conclusion

Understanding the system unit and keyboard is essential for anyone learning how computers work. The system unit houses the parts that perform tasks and store information, while the keyboard allows users to interact with and control the computer. Both are fundamental to using a computer effectively.
